Behavioral design patterns focus on how objects communicate and interact with each other. Instead of concentrating on object creation or structure, these patterns help organize responsibilities and define how different parts of an application work together, making the code easier to maintain and extend.
Some of the most commonly used behavioral design patterns include:

• Strategy :- Allows you to switch between different algorithms or behaviors without changing the code that uses them.

• State :- Changes an object’s behavior automatically when its internal state changes.

• Template :- Defines the overall structure of an algorithm while allowing specific steps to be customized.

• Iterator :- Provides a standard way to traverse a collection without exposing its internal implementation.
1. Strategy Pattern
The Strategy Pattern allows an object (known as the context) to change part of its behavior by delegating it to separate, interchangeable objects called strategies. Instead of implementing every variation of an algorithm inside the context, each strategy encapsulates a specific behavior, making it easy to switch between them when needed.
The context is responsible for the common workflow, while each strategy implements a different variation of the behavior. This allows the context to adapt its behavior based on factors such as user preferences, input values, application configuration, or runtime conditions without modifying its own code.
The Strategy Pattern is a great choice when you find yourself writing long chains of if...else or switch statements to perform different actions based on a condition. Instead of placing all the logic in a single class, you can move each behavior into its own strategy, making the code easier to read, maintain, and extend.
// Strategy Interface
class NotificationStrategy {
send(message) {
throw new Error("send() must be implemented.");
}
}// Concrete Strategies
class EmailNotification extends NotificationStrategy {
send(message) {
console.log(`📧 Sending email: ${message}`);
}
}
class SMSNotification extends NotificationStrategy {
send(message) {
console.log(`📱 Sending SMS: ${message}`);
}
}
class PushNotification extends NotificationStrategy {
send(message) {
console.log(`🔔 Sending push notification: ${message}`);
}
}
// Context
class NotificationService {
constructor(strategy) {
this.strategy = strategy;
}
setStrategy(strategy) {
this.strategy = strategy;
}
send(message) {
this.strategy.send(message);
}
}
// ------------------------
// Usage
// ------------------------
const notification = new NotificationService(
new EmailNotification()
);
notification.send("Your order has been placed.");
// Sending email: Your order has been placed.
notification.setStrategy(new SMSNotification());
notification.send("Your order has been shipped.");
// Sending SMS: Your order has been shipped.
notification.setStrategy(new PushNotification());
notification.send("Your package has been delivered.");
// Sending push notification: Your package has been delivered.
2. State Pattern
The State Pattern is a specialization of the Strategy Pattern, where the strategy changes automatically based on the current state of the context.
As we saw in the Strategy Pattern, the strategy is typically selected based on user input, configuration, or other external factors, and it usually remains unchanged. In the State Pattern, however, the strategy is dynamic and can change throughout the lifetime of the context, allowing its behavior to adapt automatically as its state changes.
A realistic example is an online order in an e-commerce application. An order can be in different states, such as Pending, Paid, Shipped, Delivered, or Cancelled. If a customer tries to cancel the order, the outcome depends on its current state. A pending order can be cancelled, a paid order may be eligible for a refund, a shipped order can no longer be cancelled, and a delivered order may instead allow the customer to request a return. Although the customer performs the same action, the system responds differently depending on the order’s current state.
The State Pattern models this behavior by assigning the responsibility for each action to the current state instead of the order itself. As the order transitions from one state to another, its behavior changes automatically without relying on complex conditional logic. This keeps the implementation clean, makes it easier to introduce new states, and improves the overall maintainability of the code.
// Base State
class OrderState {
cancel(order) {
throw new Error("cancel() must be implemented");
}
}// Pending State
class PendingState extends OrderState {
cancel(order) {
console.log("Order cancelled successfully.");
// Transition to another state
order.setState(new CancelledState());
}
}
// Paid State
class PaidState extends OrderState {
cancel(order) {
console.log("Order cancelled. Initiating refund...");
// Refund completed
console.log("Refund completed.");
order.setState(new CancelledState());
}
}
// Shipped State
class ShippedState extends OrderState {
cancel() {
console.log("Order has already been shipped and cannot be cancelled.");
}
}
// Delivered State
class DeliveredState extends OrderState {
cancel() {
console.log("Order has already been delivered. Please create a return request.");
}
}
// Cancelled State
class CancelledState extends OrderState {
cancel() {
console.log("Order is already cancelled.");
}
}
// Context
class Order {
constructor() {
this.state = new PendingState();
}
setState(state) {
this.state = state;
}
cancel() {
this.state.cancel(this);
}
}
// ------------------------
// Usage
// ------------------------
const order = new Order();
order.cancel();
// Order cancelled successfully.
order.cancel();
// Order is already cancelled.
const paidOrder = new Order();
paidOrder.setState(new PaidState());
paidOrder.cancel();
// Order cancelled. Initiating refund...
// Refund completed.
const shippedOrder = new Order();
shippedOrder.setState(new ShippedState());
shippedOrder.cancel();
// Order has already been shipped and cannot be cancelled.
const deliveredOrder = new Order();
deliveredOrder.setState(new DeliveredState());
deliveredOrder.cancel();
// Order has already been delivered. Please create a return request.
3. Template Pattern
The Template Pattern defines an abstract class that provides the overall structure (or skeleton) of an algorithm, while leaving certain steps undefined. These undefined steps, known as template methods, are implemented by subclasses to provide their own specific behavior.
The intent of this pattern is to define a family of related classes that share the same workflow but differ in the implementation of certain steps. This allows the common logic to be reused while giving each subclass the flexibility to customize specific parts of the algorithm.
Although the Strategy Pattern and Template Pattern have a similar goal of varying parts of a component while reusing the common logic, they differ in how they achieve it. The Strategy Pattern allows behavior to be changed dynamically at runtime by swapping strategies, whereas the Template Pattern determines the behavior when the subclass is created.
For this reason, the Template Pattern is a good choice when you want to provide predefined variations of a component while ensuring that the overall workflow remains consistent.
// Abstract Class
class DataImporter {
import(file) {
this.readFile(file);
const data = this.parse(file);
this.validate(data);
this.save(data);
} readFile(file) {
console.log(`Reading ${file}...`);
}
// Template Method
parse() {
throw new Error("parse() must be implemented.");
}
validate(data) {
console.log(`Validating ${data.length} records...`);
}
save(data) {
console.log(`Saving ${data.length} records to the database...`);
}
}
// Concrete Implementation
class CSVImporter extends DataImporter {
parse(file) {
console.log(`Parsing CSV file: ${file}`);
return [
{ id: 1, name: "John" },
{ id: 2, name: "Alice" },
];
}
}
class JSONImporter extends DataImporter {
parse(file) {
console.log(`Parsing JSON file: ${file}`);
return [
{ id: 1, name: "David" },
{ id: 2, name: "Emma" },
{ id: 3, name: "Sophia" },
];
}
}
// ------------------------
// Usage
// ------------------------
const csvImporter = new CSVImporter();
csvImporter.import("users.csv");
/*
Reading users.csv...
Parsing CSV file: users.csv
Validating 2 records...
Saving 2 records to the database...
*/
console.log("----------------");
const jsonImporter = new JSONImporter();
jsonImporter.import("users.json");
/*
Reading users.json...
Parsing JSON file: users.json
Validating 3 records...
Saving 3 records to the database...
*/
4. Iterator Pattern
The Iterator Pattern is one of the most fundamental and widely used design patterns in programming. It defines a common interface, or protocol, for traversing elements in a collection, such as an array, linked list, or tree. Since different data structures require different traversal algorithms, iterating over them is not always implemented in the same way. For example, traversing an array is straightforward, whereas traversing a tree often requires more complex algorithms.
The Iterator Pattern hides the underlying traversal logic and the internal structure of the collection, providing a consistent way to iterate over its elements. This allows client code to access items in a collection without needing to know how the data is stored or how the iteration is performed.
// Iterator
class EmployeeIterator {
constructor(employees) {
this.employees = employees;
this.index = 0;
} hasNext() {
return this.index < this.employees.length;
}
next() {
if (!this.hasNext()) {
return null;
}
return this.employees[this.index++];
}
}
// Collection
class EmployeeCollection {
constructor() {
this.employees = [];
}
add(employee) {
this.employees.push(employee);
}
createIterator() {
return new EmployeeIterator(this.employees);
}
}
// ------------------------
// Usage
// ------------------------
const employees = new EmployeeCollection();
employees.add({
id: 1,
name: "John",
role: "Backend Developer",
});
employees.add({
id: 2,
name: "Alice",
role: "Frontend Developer",
});
employees.add({
id: 3,
name: "David",
role: "DevOps Engineer",
});
const iterator = employees.createIterator();
while (iterator.hasNext()) {
console.log(iterator.next());
}
/*
{ id: 1, name: 'John', role: 'Backend Developer' }
{ id: 2, name: 'Alice', role: 'Frontend Developer' }
{ id: 3, name: 'David', role: 'DevOps Engineer' }
*/

Summary
Behavioral design patterns help define how objects communicate and interact with each other, making applications more flexible, maintainable, and easier to extend. In this article, we explored the Strategy, State, Template, and Iterator patterns, each addressing a different aspect of object behavior while sharing the common goal of improving code organization and reducing complexity.
